<HEADLINE>
<P>
ROCK TALK; RAISING THE VOLUME ON RAGING ARBS' RHYTHMS; VENTURA'S RENOWNED PARTY 
BAND RELEASES ITS FIRST NEW RECORDING SINCE 1985 AND CELEBRATES AT THREE 
WEEKEND GIGS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BILL LOCEY, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Experienced local rock fans may find themselves giving to the bail bondsman of 
their choice: This Memorial Day Weekend it's the Raging Arb & the Redheads' CD 
release party. These local locos will be releasing their first new music since 
1985. 
</P>
<P>
 And this little tidbit should be enough to give any party animal a case of the 
Premature Whirlies: it's not one CD release party, but three! The first one 
will be Friday night at the venerable Ventura Theatre. It's eminently 
democratic and highly affordable -- it's an all-ages show, and it's free. 
</P>
<P>
 "Just the first one will be an all-ages show," guitarist Toby Emery said. "We 
don't want this to be just another local rock night. We want to turn all the 
kids on and get a new generation of fans in there. It's their only chance to 
see us because usually we're in bars. It's a big night for us; it's a 
culmination of everything's that gone down before." 
</P>
<P>
 What's gone on before would fill the entire Life section. Suffice to say 
Raging Arb & the Redheads are Ventura's Ultimate Party Band. Kicked out of 
everywhere, blamed for everything and beloved by Venturans, the band will 
celebrate its 11th anniversary July 4. 
</P>
<P>
 The CD, which will cost about 10 bucks, features more than 50 minutes of Arb 
original music -- eight new songs and three old ones made newly gnarly for the 
'90s. The old ones are "Strut," which was on their 1985 album, "Up With The 
Joneses" and "Daze Gone By," a song whose lyrics used to change during 
performances, with Drury making them up on the spot. All of the songs have that 
trademark Arb sound -- rockin' blues with a little twang. Known for beer, 
dancing and more beer, the band has finally concocted a suitable theme song, 
"Corn Licker," which ends the CD. 
</P>
<P>
 Saturday night, the fun moves up the coast to Toes Tavern, home to 25 
different kinds of beer. For those still standing or not in custody, the party 
concludes at 2 p.m. Sunday at Eric Ericsson's on the beach in Ventura. Opening 
at all three gigs is Big Bad Voodoo Daddy, no slouches in the fun department, 
either; the band recently won three grand at an epic Battle of the Bands 
contest at Metro Bay Club in Ventura. They dress up like they fell out of a 
black and white '40s movie, and they play danceable swing music. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Another very popular Ventura dance band, Lion I's, will have its CD release 
party at the Ventura Theatre on June 10. The band has had a couple of tapes, 
but finally has a full-length CD that will contain all their biggies with the 
proper mix -- including "I'm So Poor," "Sweet Summer" and "Closer." It'll cost 
12 bucks to get into this show, but the CDs are free. 
</P>
<P>
 The other two happening local dance bands -- Ska Daddyz and Big Bad Voodoo 
Daddy -- are both in the studio working on their own CDs. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 They Come, They Go, But Mostly They Go Department: Ventura has lost three 
venues, and the year's not even half over. The Bermuda Triangle went away for 
New Year's, and last weekend Club Deja Vu in Montalvo and the Midnight Hour in 
West Ventura became history. The phone number for the manager and Club Deja Vu 
(an all-ages no booze dance club) are both disconnected -- a bad sign -- and 
alas, Montalvo rocks no more. 
</P>
<P>
 The Midnight Hour is also in the past tense after its long goodby scenario 
concluded with the third and final show Saturday night. Owner Larry Burdorf, 
who had enough fun in the last year to swear off gainful employment for good, 
says he is "actively seeking another venue." 
</P>
<P>
 On a more positive note, Nicholby's in Ventura is a viable venue and Eric 
Ericsson's, at the end of Seaward Avenue in Ventura, reopened this year after 
being closed several years. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 In the Shameful Hype Department: Did anybody go see Phish at the Arlington 
Theatre in Santa Barbara a few weeks ago? Yikes, those guys are great. That's 
about the best show I've seen in years. Four virtuoso musicians, a zillion 
original songs, and a fan network that numbers more than 50,000. Their new 
album, "Hoist," is highly recommended. 
</P>
</TEXT>
