<HEADLINE>
<P>
HORSE RACING; BIEN BIEN GETS 124, SO DOES ARCANGUES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BOB MIESZERSKI, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Bien Bien and Arcangues, who will meet for the first time in the $500,000 
Hollywood Turf Handicap on Monday, were each assigned 124 pounds for the 1 
1/4-mile race. 
</P>
<P>
 Defending champion Bien Bien carried 122 against a suspect field and won the 
San Juan Capistrano Handicap on April 24 in his last start.Arcangues also 
carried 122 pounds while winning the John Henry Handicap on May 1 in his first 
start since winning the Breeders' Cup Classic last Nov. 6. 
</P>
<P>
 "I think (Bien Bien) is one of the two most-accomplished turf horses in the 
world today," said Arcangues' trainer, Richard Mandella. "Arcangues might be 
there eventually, but right now I don't know. He won only one Group 1 grass 
race in Europe, and Bien Bien has proven himself again and again." 
</P>
<P>
 Only three others will probably run in the Grade I stake: Misil (119) and the 
Rodney Rash pair of Navarone (118) and Blues Traveller (114). Second to 
Arcangues in the John Henry, Misil worked five furlongs in 59 2/5 Wednesday, 
the best of 39 workouts at the distance. 
</P>
<P>
 Horse Racing Notes 
</P>
<P>
 Cancer, not a heart attack, killed Easy Goer, who collapsed and died outside 
his paddock at Claiborne Farm in Paris, Ky., on May 12. A necropsy done by T.W. 
Swerczek showed the malignancy had spread through the 8-year-old horse's liver, 
lungs and intestinal membranes. . . . Johnny Mc, the gelding whose identity had 
been switched with Stalvoy's for well over a month before the mistake was 
discovered a week ago, is entered in today's fourth race, a six-furlong 
allowance event for California-breds. . . . A $12 wager landed an unidentified 
person the lone perfect ticket in Sunday's Pick Six, worth $315,553.20. The 
bettor cashed the ticket at the Cabazon intertrack facility in Indio. 
</P>
