<P>
BOSNIA CLASHES HURT EFFORTS TO REVIVE TALKS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Government and Serbian forces pounded each other Wednesday in northern Bosnia, 
frustrating efforts by international negotiators to revive stalled peace talks. 
</P>
<P>
 The Yugoslav news agency Tanjug said Muslim troops were shelling Serbian 
positions around Tesanj, 60 miles northwest of Sarajevo. Tesanj and nearby 
Maglaj have been surrounded and cut off by besieging Serbs for much of the 
2-year-old war. 
</P>
<P>
 Bosnian government radio accused Serbs of shelling three towns north of 
Sarajevo and said one person was killed in shelling of Bihac in northwest 
Bosnia. 
</P>
<P>
 The fighting did not bode well for efforts by U.S., Russian and European 
envoys to revive peace talks. The envoys met separately with factional leaders 
at a mountain resort in France. 
</P>
