<HEADLINE>
<P>
4.5-MAGNITUDE QUAKE GIVES REGION'S RESIDENTS A JARRING WAKE-UP CALL; 
AFTERSHOCK: THE TEMBLOR, CENTERED NEAR THE CITY OF SAN FERNANDO, IS THE LARGEST 
TO STRIKE IN TWO MONTHS. IT WAS PARTICULARLY FELT IN EASTERN VENTURA COUNTY. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEANNETTE REGALADO and TIMOTHY WILLIAMS, TIMES STAFF WRITERS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Residents of Ventura and Los Angeles counties got a jarring wake-up call 
Wednesday morning when the largest aftershock to the Northridge earthquake in 
two months rattled the area. 
</P>
<P>
 Although the short 4.5-magnitude shaker was only powerful enough to break a 
few dishes and rattle some nerves, for many, it was a grim reminder of the 
destructive pre-dawn Jan. 17 earthquake. 
</P>
<P>
 "We felt it really good," said Malti Kasondra, 42, of Simi Valley, who was 
jolted awake and started running for the door. "I have a big house -- by the 
time I reached the door, it had stopped." 
</P>
<P>
 Kasondra, who owns a 7-Eleven store in Simi Valley, said she immediately 
called the store to check on her employees. "Only a few lightweight items fell 
off the shelves," she said. 
</P>
<P>
 The 5:56 a.m. quake, centered three miles northeast of the city of San 
Fernando, was also felt in Thousand Oaks and across eastern Ventura County, and 
as far west as Camarillo. The quake shook for as long as 15 seconds in parts of 
the San Fernando Valley and Hollywood. Caltech seismologists said it was also 
felt on Catalina Island. 
</P>
<P>
 In Ventura County, residents reported a brief but startling early-morning 
shake. 
</P>
<P>
 "It scared me at first, because I didn't know how long it was going to last," 
said Marina Glezin, 15, of Thousand Oaks. "It just shook for a second, though." 
</P>
<P>
 Throughout the day, smaller aftershocks struck many of the same areas. 
</P>
<P>
 "Probably the more emotional people were just starting to relax," said Kate 
Hutton at Caltech. "This was a pretty good feeler. It's the nature of nature, 
and we can't do much about it." 
</P>
<P>
 As jarring as the aftershock was, scientists said it was not only normal, but 
overdue. 
</P>
<P>
 Lucile M. Jones, a U. S. Geological Survey seismologist, said a computer 
analysis predicted that the area would get four aftershocks of at least 
magnitude 4 between March 20 -- the date of the last significant aftershock -- 
and Wednesday's temblor. Instead, there has been only this one, and it was a 
relatively minor one at that. 
</P>
<P>
 "This was a little less than would have been expected," Jones said. "It is not 
very typical at all." 
</P>
<P>
 Residents a few miles from the epicenter were shaken particularly hard. At the 
Tahitian Mobile Home Park in Sylmar, where 64 trailers burned after the 
Northridge quake, the jolt renewed fears. 
</P>
<P>
 "I was thinking that if it went on any longer, I would throw my body over my 
sons, and then it stopped," said Susan Rezvani, 37, standing with her two boys, 
Neema, 12, and Naveed, 4, outside a friend's trailer. 
</P>
<P>
 Otto Hofmann, 60, has lived in a motor home outside his Sylmar house since it 
was red-tagged after the Northridge quake. During Wednesday's temblor, he said, 
the trailer bounced up and down like a ball. 
</P>
<P>
 "I thought the epicenter was here ," Hofmann said. "Everybody started yelling 
and screaming, 'My God, not again!' " The only casualty in his makeshift home 
was a fax machine that fell from a shelf. 
</P>
<P>
 In other areas, the damage was minor. Cracks in the walls of homes not yet 
repaired from the January quake widened, chandeliers swung, dishes broke and 
frightened children hopped in bed with parents who could not get back to sleep. 
</P>
<P>
 There were no reported electricity, water or phone service disruptions, and no 
freeway closures, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
 Of the 8,000 aftershocks since the Jan. 17 quake, about 400 have been felt. 
Seven aftershocks were between magnitude 5.0 and 6.0; about 40 were between 4.0 
and 5.0. More than 300 were between 3.0 and 4.0. 
</P>
<P>
 The March 20 aftershock, which was magnitude 5.3 and centered near Panorama 
City, sparked two fires in the San Fernando Valley, but caused no injuries. 
</P>
<P>
 Times staff writers Kenneth Reich and Peggy Y. Lee contributed to this story. 
</P>
</TEXT>
