<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWS BITES: OUR HOURLY BREAD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARLES PERRY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Bread doesn't demand much of you while it rises -- just that you be home three 
or four hours ahead to get it started. If you don't have that luxury, you can 
add club soda or beer to a package of Quick Loaf mix, stir it up, let it sit 10 
minutes in a loaf pan and bake.The resulting loaf doesn't have the chewy, 
elastic texture of kneaded bread, but it has a good fresh-baked aroma, and for 
home-made bread that's ready one hour after you open the package, with 
essentially no work, that's not bad. The cracked wheat and nine-grain flavors 
are particularly good, and there are also garlic, onion, oatmeal and 
cinnamon-raisin mixes. In supermarkets. Swimming for the Halibut 
</P>
<P>
 Unlike other flatfish, halibut are swift swimmers and can easily rise to the 
surface to feed. In other words, they don't, as it were, flounder. CHARLES 
PERRY 
</P>
