<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWS BITES: I'LL HAVE A RIK . . . A RKATS . . . OH, MAKE IT A CHARDONNAY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAN BERGER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Wente Bros. Winery of Livermore, Calif. has agreed to invest in Sameba Co., a 
winery in the Republic of Georgia -- where some scholars believe wine was 
invented thousands of years ago.Distribution is expected to be in the four 
Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) countries where Wente now distributes 
its own California wines: Russia, Ukraine, Kazakhstan and Lithuania. UC 
Davis-trained winemaker Hughes Ryan has already moved to Georgia to supervise 
the fall's crush. The wines will be made from Rkatsitelli, a white grape, and 
Saperavi, which produces a dark red wine that ages well. "It's premature to 
say," says John Schwartz, Wente's vice president/international, "but we hope to 
produce a suitable product that meets U.S. standards within two to five years." 
DAN BERGER 
</P>
</TEXT>
