<HEADLINE>
<P>
 COMMUNITY NEWS: POLSKYS REACH TRUCE IN BATTLE OVER NAME 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By EMILY ADAMS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Two unrelated lawyers named Polsky who have been warring in the courts over 
use of that surname may have found an uneasy compromise. At least the signs 
point that way. 
</P>
<P>
 Alexander Polsky, a Long Beach lawyer who is running for Municipal Court 
judge, has put up new campaign signs around town, including his first name. 
</P>
<P>
 And Trudy Polsky, a real estate attorney and Long Beach City College trustee, 
has put her lawsuit on the back burner -- for now. 
</P>
<P>
 Friction between the Polskys began when Alexander Polsky posted signs around 
town advertising "Polsky . . . Municipal Court Judge." Trudy Polsky said he was 
attempting to cash in on her name recognition and filed a lawsuit, asking that 
he be forced to include his first name. 
</P>
<P>
 Trudy Polsky said she has taken her motion off the court's calendar. EMILY 
ADAMS 
</P>
